hemes served simultaneously as a practical method of controlling colonial subjects and as a rationale for imposing a neo-imperial international governance, with long-standing consequences for the region. Placing the histories of Iraq, Palestine, and Syria within a global context of emerging state systems intent on creating new forms of international authority, in States of Separation Laura Robson sheds new light on the emergence of ethnic separatism in the modern Middle East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aForced migrationzMiddle East. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aanti semitism.  aarab.  aarmenian.  aassyrian.  abritish occupation.  acommunity.  aculture.  aethnic divide.  aethnic separation.  aeuropean history.  aexperimental.  afrench occupation.  airaq.  ajewish.  aleague of nations.  amiddle east.  amiddle eastern history.  amilitary strategy.  amuslim.  aottoman.  apalestine.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apopulation.  apost war.  aracial divide.  aracism.  areligion.  areligious divide.  areligious majority.  areligious minority.  astrategy.  asyria.  aviolence.  awartime.  aworld history.  awwi.  azionist.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029215440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965669?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965669423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965669/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY